What is a Graph in DSA?

A Graph is a non-linear data structure used to represent relationships between different objects.

It consists of:

Vertices (Nodes) → Represent entities

Edges → Represent connections between vertices

🔹 Real-Life Examples

🗺 Google Maps → Cities connected by roads

🌐 Social networks → People connected by friendships

✈ Flight routes → Airports connected by flights

💻 Internet → Computers connected by cables

All these are modeled using graphs.

🔹 Basic Terminology

If we have:

A ---- B
|      |
D ---- C

A, B, C, D → Vertices

Lines between them → Edges

🔹 Types of Graphs
1️⃣ Undirected Graph

Edges have no direction.

Example:

A ---- B

If A is connected to B, B is also connected to A.

2️⃣ Directed Graph (Digraph)

Edges have direction.

A → B

A points to B, but B may not point to A.

3️⃣ Weighted Graph

Edges have weights (cost, distance, time).

Example:

A --5-- B

Weight = 5

4️⃣ Unweighted Graph

Edges have no cost.

🔹 How Graph is Represented in Code?
1️⃣ Adjacency Matrix (2D Array)
int graph[4][4];

Uses 2D array

Space: O(V²)

2️⃣ Adjacency List (Most Used)

Using STL:

#include <vector>
using namespace std;

vector<int> adj[5];

Example:

adj[0].push_back(1);
adj[1].push_back(0);

Space: O(V + E) ✅ (Better)

